      textEn: [
        "Dear Alma Mater,\n\nAs I write this letter, the parasol trees outside have turned green again. I remember on my first day of school, this tree was only as tall as me. Now its branches spread wide, casting a great canopy of shade. Six years \u2014 I\u2019ve grown up alongside this tree.",
        "I can\u2019t forget the little path through campus. In spring, cherry blossoms line both sides, pink petals carpeting the ground \u2014 nobody wanted to step on them. In summer, the big locust trees cast cool shade for jumping rope and string games. In autumn, ginkgo leaves turned golden and we pressed fan-shaped leaves between pages as bookmarks. In winter after snow, the path became a natural skating rink \u2014 we\u2019d walk carefully, slip, and laugh in a heap.",
        "I can\u2019t forget the little blackboard bulletin in the back of our classroom. Every month, I\u2019d help design it \u2014 drawing borders, writing headlines, copying content. Sometimes we\u2019d stay late, hands covered in chalk dust, but seeing classmates gathered around reading the next day made it all worthwhile.",
        "I can\u2019t forget the cafeteria auntie\u2019s braised pork. Every Wednesday at noon, the aroma drifted up to the third floor. She\u2019d always smile and give me an extra scoop: \u2018Eat more, grow taller!\u2019 That taste I\u2019ll probably never forget.",
        "Dear Alma Mater, I spent the six most carefree years of my life in your embrace. You taught me to read and write, taught me how to be a good person, and gave me the purest joy. Though graduation is near, I know that wherever I go, I will always be your child.\n\nWith deepest respect,\n\nYour student\nJune 2026"
      ],
